and less energy.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>However, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_the_Headless_Chicken\" rel=\"nofollow\">chickens can live without its head<\/a> as long as the injury does not significantly damage its brain stem, which controls the animal's vital reflexes such as respirations.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Chickens do have complex network of blood vessels and capillaries.<\/li>\n<li>Chickens don't breathe via spiracles and do have centralized respiration system like us.<\/li>\n<li>Chickens are warm-blooded.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Thus, an animal (such as a cockroach) can live headless if its remaining organs can still control its \"vital functions\".<\/p>\n","answer_id":24166,"question_id":23842,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1416459697}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/23842/why-does-a-cockroach-not-die-even-after-decapitation","last_activity_date":1453738745,"creation_date":1415537863,"answer_count":3,"title":"Why does a cockroach not die even after decapitation?","body":"<p>Why does a cockroach not die after its head is cut off?<\/p>\n","question_id":23842,"tags":["entomology"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":23847,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1451,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1415559337},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/313b8e75624eea45f7de829ad3691828?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21406,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21406/pat3d3r","reputation":11,"display_name":"pat3d3r"},"closed_date":1453804681,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":42643,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453730318,"comment_id":73402,"body":"Stopping drugs/alcohol &quot;cold turkey&quot; <i>ca