tructure of your proteins.<\/p>\n\n<p>If your proteins have not been structure determined, the next best thing is some kind of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homology_modeling\" rel=\"nofollow\">homology model<\/a>, that is, a prediction of your protein structure based on a known structure of a homologous protein. These can be more or less accurate, depending on how close the homolog protein is. If specific domains are interacting, it may be enough to create a model of the domain only.<\/p>\n\n<p>There are online tools available for homology modeling, for example <a href=\"http://swissmodel.expasy.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\">swiss-model<\/a> from the expasy site. This is not an automated process though --- creating an accurate model requires some skills. You should read the publications describing these tools and make sure you understand the process and error souces, and perhaps contact an expert if in doubt. Good luck!<\/p>\n","answer_id":42621,"question_id":42609,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42609/how-to-predict-protein-protein-interactions-from-a-pair-of-gene-symbols","last_activity_date":1453639587,"creation_date":1453588458,"answer_count":1,"title":"How to predict Protein-Protein Interactions from a pair of gene symbols?","body":"<p>I have a list of pairs of gene symbols who interact (putatively) and would like to assign each pair a score (and record other details) based on the predicted Protein-Protein Interaction (PPI). The existing PPI webservers I've looked at (<a href=\"http://cluspro.bu.edu/home.php\" rel=\"nofollow\">ClusPro<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.bonvinlab.org/software/haddock2.2/haddock.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">HADDOCK<\/a>) require that I use <a href=\"http://www.rcsb.org/pdb/home/home.do\" rel=\"nofollow\">PDB<\/a> ID's as input. Unfortunately, PDB ID's don't always exist for the gene symbols I'd like to compare. I believe I need either:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>a way to generate PDB files myself (perhaps with a folding program?) and then connect/upload them to a PPI webserver.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>or<\/p>\n\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>a way to find the most similar sequence that does have a PDB ID and upload it to a PPI webserver. <\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Am I understanding my problem correctly? Are there resources that can help with 1 or 2?<\/p>\n","question_id":42609,"tags":["protein-folding","protein-interaction","pdb"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":25,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/18f18ce255fa3d3a99ed127f9a70aad5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5688,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5688/questionhang","reputation":260,"display_name":"questionhang","accept_rate":33},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":42510,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453342078,"comment_id":73092,"body":"The organ from person A will never have it&#39;s DNA replaced to match that of its new host B. This is actually a good thing, because many organ transplants are done to treat genetic diseases. If the new organ had its DNA replaced with the host&#39;s faulty DNA, the transplant would be ruined. As far as detecting the organ&#39;s foreign DNA in its new host, that depends on how the sample was collected. If you look really hard at DNA in blood samples, you <b>might<\/b> find some evidence of the donor&#39;s DNA in the host&#39;s blood, but how much probably depends on what organ was transplanted and other factors."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/18f18ce255fa3d3a99ed127f9a70aad5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5688,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5688/questionhang","reputation":260,"display_name":"questionhang","accept_rate":33},"score":0,"post_id":42510,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1453536669,"comment_id":73276,"body":"@user137 But cells of the new organ may die and be replaced at least. The new cells have the host&#39;s DNA or the new organ&#39;s DNA?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":42510,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453612192,"comment_id":73344,"body":"If the transplanted organ&#39;s cells die, they probably have to be replaced by other cells in the transplanted organ. These would carry the foreign DNA from the donor. The only way for new cells in the organ to carry the host&#39;s DNA would be if host cells colonized the new organ from the outside, which doesn&#39;t seem significant. There are cells that can colonize tissues, such as Kupffer cells in the Liver, but these don&#39;t make up the bulk of the liver, those are hepatocytes."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/24QpY.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16539,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16539/colombo","reputation":307,"display_name":"Colombo"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/18f18ce255fa3d3a99ed127f9a70aad5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5688,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5688/questionhang","reputation":260,"display_name":"ques