 in the answers below)."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/15894a0d103ab92a2cd3b1000efca418?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6422,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6422/cornelius","reputation":6008,"display_name":"Cornelius"},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9739ec5574d9977b522d1c80fb8de84?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6149,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6149/lie-ryan","reputation":101,"display_name":"Lie Ryan"},"score":2,"post_id":21078,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410058168,"comment_id":33046,"body":"Not eating or drinking and Metabolic processing does not change your weight/mass, that violates conservation of mass. The only thing that affects body mass are excrements (from urine, sweat, and faeces), respiration, and very small amount of debris from your skin/hair."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/91a78cf1465182161a79685058d8b39b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":9122,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9122/nanne","reputation":101,"display_name":"Nanne"},"score":1,"post_id":21078,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410076814,"comment_id":33049,"body":"Mass can be converted into engergy. Setting something on fire does change the weight/mass of for instance your house, doesn&#39;t it? This is what your body does when you &quot;burn&quot; calories. You don&#39;t eat (add something), but your body stays 37 degrees -&gt; the energy to keep it that temperature (even ignoring things like heartbeat and other processes like your brain) has to come from somewhere. Apart from that, the law of conseveration of mass deals with closed systems (also closed for energy!) which you body certainly isn&#39;t."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e032a74b26c2116bfcad775ffdc45ae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6166/iqandreas","reputation":185,"display_name":"IQAndreas"},"score":0,"post_id":21078,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/91a78cf1465182161a79685058d8b39b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":9122,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9122/nanne","reputation":101,"display_name":"Nanne"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1410078037,"comment_id":33052,"body":"@Nanne Mass isn&#39;t &quot;converted to energy&quot;, at least not in our human body (unless we go thermonuclear, which would be awesome, but just doesn&#39;t happen). What we do when we &quot;burn&quot; calories is break the chemical bonds between glucose(?) molecules; the breaking of these bonds releases the small amount of energy stored in them by the plants that spent that same amount of energy in order to produce those bonds. The combined mass of the &quot;broken apart&quot; molecules is still the same as the &quot;complete&quot; <code>C6H12O6<\/code> molecule."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e032a74b26c2116bfcad775ffdc45ae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6166/iqandreas","reputation":185,"display_name":"IQAndreas"},"score":0,"post_id":21078,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410078232,"comment_id":33054,"body":"(If a biologist or chemist could double-check my comment, I wasn&#39;t sure if it was glucose or sucrose that gets broken apart. Moreover, as I only have a basic understanding in the field, I may have other minor flaws in my comment)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e032a74b26c2116bfcad775ffdc45ae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6166/iqandreas","reputation":185,"display_name":"IQAndreas"},"score":0,"post_id":21078,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"htt