e,"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1410045672,"creation_date":1410045672,"body":"<p>There is only one way to gain weight, consume things. Thus after any period of time not consuming anything (i.e. sleeping) we must necessarily weigh &lt;= what we weighted at the start of that time period. Add in respiration, and that becomes a strict inequality!<\/p>\n","answer_id":21086,"question_id":21076,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e032a74b26c2116bfcad775ffdc45ae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6166/iqandreas","reputation":185,"display_name":"IQAndreas"},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e032a74b26c2116bfcad775ffdc45ae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6166/iqandreas","reputation":185,"display_name":"IQAndreas"},"score":0,"post_id":21092,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410080707,"comment_id":33056,"body":"<code>*<\/code> Technically <i>calorie<\/i> is a unit of energy and not an item that can be &quot;burned&quot;. What we mean when we use the word is the process of molecules being broken apart, which releases energy that can be used by the body; however, the pieces of the &quot;broken up&quot; molecules still weigh the same as the molecule as a whole, so we don&#39;t loose weight just from &quot;burning calories&quot;."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1453605798,"creation_date":1410080312,"body":"<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCHnyfMqiRRG1u-2MsSQLbXA\" rel=\"nofollow\">Veritasium<\/a> created <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lL2e0rWvjKI\" rel=\"nofollow\">an excellent video just on this topic<\/a>, which I would recommend watching, but will summarize here.<\/p>\n\n<p>A common misconception is that we lose weight when we digest food or burn calories. Keep in mind that that broken down food and those calories<code>*<\/code> aren't \"going anywhere\", so technically you shouldn't loose any mass (unless you get rid of the molecules by going to the restroom).<\/p>\n\n<p>However, in the \"informal\" tests done by Derek Muller, <strong>he lost about 250 grams each night<\/strong>. Since during the night you sweat (which evaporates or gets absorbed into the sheets and blankets), he estimated that about <strong>150 grams was lost through perspiration and breathing out water vapor<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The more surprising loss of mass, was 0.012 grams of carbon lost with each breath when breathing in oxygen, and then breathing out carbon dioxide. Although this seems like a tiny loss, assuming you breathe in and out about 7,680 times each night, that tiny mass loss adds up to almost <strong>100 grams of weight loss through breathing alone<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>I guess health magazines should start running articles like <em>\"Top way to lose more weight? Researchers say breathe more!\"<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n","answer_id":21092,"question_id":21076,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1453605798}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/21076/why-do-we-weigh-less-in-the-morning","last_activity_date":1453605798,"creation_date":1410021431,"answer_count":3,"title":"Why do we weigh less in the morning?","body":"<p>At first I thought it may be related to physics.  You know, in one half of the day, the gravity changes, and the scale shows a different weight than the other.  Then at night, gravity intensifies, and you become slightly heavier.<\/p>\n\n<p>But I'm a bit skeptical about that. Is that true?  That it's somehow related to gravitational fields? <\/p>\n","question_id":21076,"tags":["metabolism","circadian-rhythms"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":1,"protected_date":1453569708,"is_answered":true,"view_count":7451,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1410022138},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/265a636403a666dfd073e77e2