 link to the image you included and perhaps a comment on the discrepancy. Finally, could you present a citation or key indicating the importance of sternites (and other characteristics). Thanks!!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":1,"post_id":42565,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1nMw6.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16866,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16866/theforestecologist","reputation":1908,"display_name":"theforestecologist","accept_rate":14},"edited":false,"creation_date":1453587625,"comment_id":73331,"body":"@theforestecologist Most of the nomenclature discrepancy I suspect is  from the fact the article by Hamilton is trying to do something different. I can&#39;t quote you on when the distinction was made, but R2+3 means that the vein R2 and the vein R3 coalesce through their extent in a single vein. Here&#39;s your image source <a href=\"http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/6270326#page/328/mode/1up\" rel=\"nofollow\">biodiversitylibrary.org/page/6270326#page/328/mode/1up<\/a> .. for more on the nomenclature, <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/2452973?seq=4#page_scan_tab_contents\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":1,"post_id":42565,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453587888,"comment_id":73332,"body":"It&#39;s  my thought while researching this that Tabanus is rather poorly defined!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1nMw6.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered