e xylem and the phloem in the stem and root of a vascular plant, and is the source of both the secondary xylem growth (inwards, towards the pith <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vascular_cambium\" rel=\"nofollow\">material at the center of plant, often dead and/or deteriorated, that is composed of parenchyma tissue<\/a>) and the secondary phloem growth (outwards [to the bark, rough or smooth, of the plant]). It is a cylinder of unspecialized meristem cells that divide to give new cells which then specialize to form secondary vascular tissues.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Intra fascicular cambium<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>From <a href=\"http://www.biology.lifeeasy.org/5040/what-is-intrafascicular-cambium\" rel=\"nofollow\">Biology.easlife<\/a><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The cambial strip which is present between the primary xylem and primary phloem is known as the intra fascicular cambium. The intra fascicular cambium is also known as the vascular cambium. During the secondary growth the cambial ring is formed by the inter connection of the intra fascicular and inter fascicular cambium. - See more at: <a href=\"http://www.biology.lifeeasy.org/5040/what-is-intrafascicular-cambium#sthash.aY3SPblI.dpuf\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.biology.lifeeasy.org/5040/what-is-intrafascicular-cambium#sthash.aY3SPblI.dpuf<\/a><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>What is the difference between fascicular cambium and inter fascicular cambium?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>From <a href=\"http://www.biology.lifeeasy.org/5059/difference-between-fascicular-cambium-fascicular-cambium\" rel=\"nofollow\">biology.lifeeasy<\/a><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The cambium present within the vascular bundle is called intra fascicular cambium or vascular cambium. It is present between the primary xylem and primary phloem. The intra fascicular cambium is primary in origin.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>The new strip of cambium which is formed from the permanent cells of inter fascicular parenchyma is called the inter fascicular cambium.  The inter fascicular cambium is secondary in origin since it is derived from the permanent cells of medullary rays.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Need more?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>If the above definitions don't help, you should include in your question why these definitions don't help and what is unclear.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42604,"question_id":42600,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42600/what-is-vascular-cambium","last_activity_date":1453580011,"creation_date":1453577049,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is vascular cambium?","body":"<p>I'm confused over the two terms vascular cambium and intrafascicular cambium.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is vascular cambium same as intrafascicular cambium?<\/p>\n","question_id":42600,"tags":["botany"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":42604,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":56,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f06106f04bf2c5bc8d096dbd7a13e41?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":941,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/941/markokram","reputation":277,"display_name":"MarkokraM","accept_rate":75},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42602/is-there-a-joint-on-a-brain-connecting-both-inner-speech-and-outer-speech-sensat","last_activity_date":1453578109,"creation_date":1453577616,"answer_count":0,"title":"Is there a joint on a brain connecting both inner speech and outer speech sensation?","body":"<p>I'm interested of the neurophysiology of the inner speech/inner voice aka. auditory thinking. This question is similar to: <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41092/is-there-a-difference-between-visual-sensation-and-imagination-in-the-brain\">What are the common neural circuitries between visual sensation and the imagination of sensation?<\/a> but now concerning auditory system.<\/p>\n\n<p>Long article about the topic I found from: <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4538954/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4538954/<\/a> and I was watching Neuroanatomy from youtube: <a href=\"https://youtu.be/4c4h3WfF3kA?t=18m49s\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://youtu.be/4c4h3WfF3kA?t=18m49s<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Is it possible to determine if inner phonological loop has the same entry point to the auditory system quite near to the inner ear or her to the place where nerves from the inner ear joins to the other part of the brain?<\/p>\n","question_id":42602,"tags":["brain","human-ear","language"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":9,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1453578109},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/19be8736bcd0dd31e6c487d84baa689d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21372,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21372/neuronerd","reputation":8,"display_name":"Neuronerd"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f524f51edb2e0e559de5f027217b2d47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14815,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14815/ro-siv","reputation":535,"display_name":"Ro Siv","accept_rate":97},"score":1,"post_id":42599,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453573774,"comment_id":73313,"body":"Maybe they meant noise as a type of interference, like when you have everyone in the same room with the same type of wireless mouse, there is interference with the signal. Thats just a Wild A$$ Guess though..."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1453577583,"creation_date":1453577583,"body":"<p>The term <code>noise<\/code> can mean a number of different (more or les related) things is used in a number of different fields such as signal processing, psychology and statistics.<\/p>\n\n<p>Outside of its context, it is impossible to say for certitude what you professors were referring to.<\/p>\n\n<p>The quotations below come from <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication_noise\" rel=\"nofollow\">wikipedia > Communication noise<\/a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_noise\" rel=\"nofollow\">wikipedia > Statistical noise<\/a>, <a href=\"http://In%20signal%20processing,%20white%20noise%20is%20a%20random%20signal%20with%20a%20constant%20power%20spectral%20density.[1]%20The%20term%20is%20used,%20with%20this%20or%20similar%20meanings,%20in%20many%20scientific%20and%20technical%20disciplines,%20including%20physics,%20acoustic%20engineering,%20telecommunications,%20statistical%20forecasting,%20and%20many%20more.%20White%20noise%20refers%20to%20a%20statistical%20model%20for%20signals%20and%20signal%20sources,%20rather%20than%20to%20any%20specific%20signal.\">wikipedia > white noise<\/a> and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noise\" rel=\"nofollow\">wikipedia > noise<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Psychological noise<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Psychological noise results from preconceived notions we bring to conversations, such as racial stereotypes, reputations, biases, and assumptions. When we come into a conversation with ideas about what the other person is going to say and why, we can easily become blinded to their original message. Most of the time psychological noise is impossible to free ourselves from, and we must simply strive to recognize that it exists and take those distractions into account when we converse with others.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Psychological noise<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Physiological noise has to do with distractions from the natural effects of the body, such as being tired or hungry.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Physical noise<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Physical noise is any external or environmental stimulus that distracts us from receiving the intended message sent by a communicator (Rothwell 11). Examples of physical noise include: others talking in the background, background music, a startling noise and acknowledging someone outside of the conversation.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Semantic noise<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>This is noise caused by the sender. i.e., the encoder. This type of noise occurs when grammar or technical language is used that the receiver (the decoder) cannot understand, or cannot understand it clearly. It occurs when the sender of the message uses a word or a phrase that we don't know the meaning of, or which we use in a different way from the speakers. This is usually due to the result that the encoder had failed to practice audience analysis at first. The type of audience is the one that determine the jargon one will use.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Statistical noise<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Statistical noise is the colloquialism for recognized amounts of unexplained variation in a sample.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>White noise<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In signal processing, white noise is a random signal with a constant power spectral density.<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication_noise\" rel=\"nofollow\">1<\/a> The term is used, with this or similar meanings, in many scientific and technical disciplines, including physics, acoustic engineering, telecommunications, statistical forecasting, and many more. White noise refers to a statistical model for signals and signal sources, rather than to any specific signal.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Noise in its everyday use<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Noise is a variety of sound. It means any unwanted sound. Sounds, particularly loud ones, that disturb people or make it difficult to hear wanted sounds, are noise. For example, conversations of other people may be called noise by people not involved in any of them; any unwanted sound such as domesticated dogs barking, neighbours playing loud music, portable mechanical saws, road traffic sounds, or a distant aircraft in quiet countryside, is called noise.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":42601,"question_id":42599,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42599/what-is-noise","last_activity_date":1453577583,"creation_date":1453573569,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is 'noise'?","body":"<p>In both my psychology, biology and neuroscience classes, professors are constantly talking about 'noise'. For instance, our perception is limited due to 'sensory noise' in our neurons. \nI am utterly confused about this concept. What is 'noise'? Can someone please conceptually describe what is is in laymen's terms?  <\/p>\n","question_id":42599,"tags":["human-biology","molecular-biology","neuroscience","psychophysics"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":42601,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":44,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7819f202df153ed141e0b50ad291ae06?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6950,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6950/cherry8-8vanilla","reputation":116,"display_name":"cherry8.8vanilla","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1453572378,"creation_date":1453572378,"body":"<p>These are somewhat loosely defined terms, but I would say catabolism is any metabolic process that extracts energy from a substrate. Ethanol conversion to acetate (via alcohol dehydrogenase; <a href=\"http://humancyc.org/HUMAN/NEW-IMAGE?type=PATHWAY&amp;object=PWY66-21\">see this schematic<\/a>) is an oxidative pathway which extracts energy in the form of NADH, so yes, it is a catabolic pathway.<\/p>\n\n<p>I guess you can also call this process detoxification, since it removes a (mildly) toxic metabolite. Anyway, I think the \"classification\" of a pathway is less important than understanding the actual biochemistry.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42598,"question_id":42585,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42585/why-is-metabolism-of-ethanol-catabolism-could-it-be-also-detoxification","last_activity_date":1453572378,"creation_date":1453552371,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is metabolism of ethanol catabolism? Could it be also detoxification?","body":"<p><strong>Detoxification<\/strong> is the physiological or medicinal removal of toxic substances from a living organism, including the human body, which is mainly carried out by the liver. Additionally, it can refer to the period of withdrawal during which an organism returns to homeostasis after long-term use of an addictive substance. (Source: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detoxification\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detoxification<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>Ethanol is metabolised in liver with ADH, which oxidises ethanol to acetaldehyde. The latter is a toxic substance and can cause tissue damage, therfore, it must be further oxidised by ALDH to form a non-toxic product, acetate.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Ethanol can be an addictive substance.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Why is ethanol metabolism catagorized as catabolism? Could it also be detoxification (according to the assumptions above)? Why not?<\/p>\n\n<p>Is ethanol metabolism a catabolic metabolic pathway because it provides NADH and acetate (which can be activated to acetyl-CoA) for anabolic reactions? Or is there another reason?<\/p>\n","question_id":42585,"tags":["biochemistry"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":42598,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":46,"up_vo