 number of genes then you can investigate them separately. Use a statistical test to verify the significance of your correlation between histone mark and expression. If the discordance is widespread, then I would suggest you to repeat the RNAseq (easier and cheaper than repeating ChIP-seq). BTW, how were the read qualities? Depending on that you can decide which experiment needs repetition. Repetition will help you to know if the observation is indeed correct (a biological replicate); possibly you may end also up concluding that these marks are actually dicey.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>If a few genes show discordance, then just do Real-Time PCR for these genes. RT-PCR is more sensitive and another technique of quantification is anyways good. Use a few concordant genes also, in the experiment. <\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":42434,"question_id":42425,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1453227995},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dbf7db222a1b26ef78becec9676969a2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21278,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21278/jared-andrews","reputation":176,"display_name":"Jared Andrews"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9505b9216fdae1f6735ed821cfa7e7f8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14834,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14834/tonja","reputation":238,"display_name":"Tonja","accept_rate":67},"score":0,"post_id":42479,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453219053,"comment_id":73032,"body":"I checked the promoter histones as well and I have also some genes that are not supported by RNA-seq. I know I could validate the results but that is encode data. So, I would like just to know the theoretical reason for that."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dbf7db222a1b26ef78becec9676969a2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21278,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21278/jared-andrews","reputation":176,"display_name":"Jared Andrews"},"score":0,"post_id":42479,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9505b9216fdae1f6735ed821cfa7e7f8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14834,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14834/tonja","reputation":238,"display_name":"Tonja","accept_rate":67},"edited":false,"creation_date":1453221045,"comment_id":73036,"body":"What is encode data? The RNA-seq?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":42479,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453222759,"comment_id":73039,"body":"@JaredAndrews I think Tonja is referring to the TFBS ChIP-seqs.."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dbf7db222a1b26ef78becec9676969a2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21278,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21278/jared-andrews","reputation":176,"display_name":"Jared Andrews"},"score":1,"post_id":42479,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1453226915,"comment_id":73046,"body":"@WYSIWYG If that&#39;s the case, I&#39;d suggest looking at different marks, as they certainly have them if they also have H3K79me2 and H3K36me3. The epigenome is complex, flexible, and variant. As such, you should look at the pieces as a whole whenever possible."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1453222769,"creation_date":1453215497,"body":"<p>ChIP-seq isn't perfect. Even between technical replicates, you get a fair amount of variation, especially for broad marks like those you're using. It's rather uncommon to see people use H3K79me2 and H3K36me3 to determine if a gene's expressed or not. Using H3K4me3 and H3K27ac or H3ac is a more common method of marking promoters of transcribed genes. <\/p>\n\n<p>40 genes discordant wouldn't worry me much unless you really have low reads for either set of sequencing experiments. @WYSIWYG's suggestion to use RT-PCR to verify your RNA-seq data for a few genes is a good one. <\/p>\n","answer_id":42479,"question_id":42425,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1453222769}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42425/chip-seq-for-histone-modification-not-in-agreement-with-rna-seq-for-expression","last_activity_date":1453227995,"creation_date":1453063723,"answer_count":2,"title":"ChIP-seq for histone modification not in agreement with RNA-seq for expression","body":"<p>I have ChIP-seq for H3K79me2 and H3K36me3 and RNA-seq data for treated and untreated samples. Those two histones mark active genes. Lets say, hypothetically, a peak caller finds differential sites at gene A for both of those histone modifications. However, when I run RNA-seq analysis tools (like edgeR or DESeq2) this gene is not marked as differentially expressed (well it has a FDR value of >0.05). <\/p>\n\n<p>There might be several technical reasons for RNA-seq analysis methods not to find this gene as differentially expressed because<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>it is really not differentially expressed<\/li>\n<li>or it is not differentially expressed enough for the tools to detect it<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>However, I am more interested in the biological aspect. If two histones mark gene A as active in treated samples, one would expect that it would be expressed in RNA-seq. What mechanism could lead to the result that however the genes is marked as active by histones, it will not be differentially expressed in RNA-seq?<\/p>\n","question_id":42425,"tags":["molecular-genetics","rna-sequencing","histone","chip","histone-modifications"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":42434,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":52,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1453100824},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"score":1,"post_id":42327,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452798661,"comment_id":72630,"body":"Thanks so much for your thorough response, this question was bothering me. But I see how one would arrive at that answer now."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":42327,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452802806,"comment_id":72633,"body":"Are you saying that for the answer to be multiple alleles, each phenotype needs to be represented my an allele? So one Red, one Orange, and one Yellow? Is that the technical definition of multiple alleles for inheritance? It seems like that is a bit of a confusing answer choice, as there have to be different alleles for red and yellow, at a minimum."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.c