\/p>\n\n<p>If it were the latter (white eye male) that would leave two further possibilities, mothers are homo- or heterozygous for the dominant red eye allele. If the mother is homozygous for the red allele then all offspring should have red eyes, all will receive an X that carries the dominant red eye allele.  If the mother is heterozygous then half of the offspring will be red eyed and half white eyed, because both of the fathers sex chromosomes do not have the red allele (the X and the Y) and only one of the mothers carries it.<\/p>\n\n<p>In the exercise, you have <em>some<\/em> white eyed flies in the first offspring, but not all, and most are red eyed. Given the wording of the question (that <em>red eyed <strong>flies<\/strong> were mated to white eyed <strong>flies<\/em><\/strong>, and not <em>a red eyed <strong>fly<\/strong> was mated to a white eyed <strong>fly<\/em><\/strong>) I would suggest that the first generation was produced by crossing multiple red eyed females to multiple white eyed males, and that the females were a mixture of hetero- and homozygotes. Therefore <em>some<\/em> of the offspring were white eyed. The point being, <strong>with the first cross it is impossible to tell whether the females used were each hetero- or homozygotes, you can't deduce their genotype.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ukz05.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ukz05.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>In the second cross, both parents have red eyes. What this tells you is that the fathers have an X chromosome with the dominant red eye allele, and the mothers have <em>at least<\/em> one X with the dominant red eye allele. They produce sons and daughters, among which, 1/4 are white eyed males, and none are white eyed females. The <em>implied/logical<\/em> further outcome is then that 1/4 of the offspring were red eyed males, and 1/2 (2/4) were red eyed females. In the second cross <strong>the mothers must be heterozygous<\/strong> (have just one red eye carrying X chromosome). The key difference here is that you can establish the <em>genotype<\/em> of the parental flies. <\/p>\n\n<p>The cross below shows this. The sons, who inherit an X from their mother and Y from their father, are white eyed half of the time because there is a 50% chance of inheriting a red eye X from the mother and 0% chance of inheriting a red eye X from the father. Females are always red eyed because the X comes from the father, and he has only one X (which carries the red eyed allele). Half of the daughters will be heterozygous, and half homozygous, for the red eye allele, but it is dominant so all have the red eye phenotype.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/eBaJm.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/eBaJm.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>I assume that recombination cannot occur in males (<a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7267/why-doesnt-recombination-occur-in-male-drosophila\"><em>D. melanogaster<\/em> has no recombination in males<\/a>) and therefore has nothing to do with the solution, but that depends which species of fruit fly the example refers to - could you clarify? It appears this is <a href=\"https://books.google.se/books?id=iCJbCwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA61&amp;lpg=PA61&amp;dq=When%20red-eyed%20flies%20(dominant)%20were%20mated%20with%20white-eyed%20flies%20(recessive),%20most,%20but%20not%20all,%20of%20the%20F1%20progeny%20were%20red%20eyed.%20Furthermore,%20when%20the%20red-eyed%20males%20of%20the%20F1%20generation%20were%20mated%20with%20their%20red-eyed%20sisters,%20they%20produced%20about%20one-quarter%20white-eyed%20males,%20but%20no%20white-eyed%20females.%20In%20other%20words,%20the%20eye%20color%20phenotype%20was%20sex-linked.&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=R2TI57YSkg&amp;sig=NZzHd_BPzQqk08VU0itwaE-zt8I&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwiz5auHsLPKAhVFkSwKHStzA8oQ6AEIIjAB#v=onepage&amp;q=When%20red-eyed%20flies%20(dominant)%20were%20mated%20with%20white-eyed%20flies%20(recessive)%2C%20most%2C%20but%20not%20all%2C%20of%20the%20F1%20progeny%20were%20red%20eyed.%20Furthermore%2C%20when%20the%20red-eyed%20males%20of%20the%20F1%20generation%20were%20mated%20with%20their%20red-eyed%20sisters%2C%20they%20produced%20about%20one-quarter%20white-eyed%20males%2C%20but%20no%20white-eyed%20females.%20In%20other%20words%2C%20the%20eye%20color%20phenotype%20was%20sex-linked.&amp;f=false\" rel=\"nofollow\">this book<\/a>, and therefore it is <em>D. melanogaster<\/em>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42444,"question_id":42432,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1453120765}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42432/simple-mendelian-sex-linked-chromosome-fruit-fly-question","last_activity_date":1453120765,"creation_date":1453091658,"answer_count":2,"title":"Simple Mendelian sex-linked chromosome fruit fly question","body":"<p>From my molecular biology textbook:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>When red-eyed flies (dominant) were mated with white-eyed flies (recessive), most, but not all, of the F1 progeny were red eyed. Furthermore, when the red-eyed males of the F1 generation were mated with their red-eyed sisters, they produced about one-quarter white-eyed males, but no white-eyed females. In other words, the eye color phenotype was sex-linked.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>First, wouldn't recombination scramble the eye color alleles among the sex chromosomes?<\/p>\n\n<p>Secondly, even without recombination, the F1 generation will be heterozygous and all F1 flies will have white and red alleles. Some F1 males will have a white X and some F1 females will have a white X, in which case it should be possibly to have an F2 white fly.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can someone explain this?<\/p>\n","question_id":42432,"tags":["genetics"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":93,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1453099101},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ff7e44f9872ea7fe7bd52611dba1036?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20805,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20805/jon-wilcox","reputation":46,"display_name":"Jon Wilcox"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":42443,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453126326,"comment_id":72954,"body":"To make proteins you  just need mRNAs. And most of the synthesis (transcription) is done in the S-phase, including the mRNAs required for later stages."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/56b4833d86d3cccc3ccfd6eeaf0b767e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14946,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14946/mdperry","reputation":2645,"display_name":"mdperry"},"score":0,"post_id":42443,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453172986,"comment_id":72989,"body":"Consider two values, the average half-life of an mRNA, and the average half-life of a protein.  A cell may not need to transcribe it&#39;s essential genes non-stop."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42443/is-dna-transcription-inactive-during-mitosis-ie-no-proteins-are-made-how-does-t","last_activity_date":1453118698,"creation_date":1453118698,"answer_count":0,"title":"Is DNA transcription inactive during mitosis ie no proteins are made? How does the cell survive?","body":"<p>I've read that during mitosis, DNA exists as heterochromatin, a form that is unable to be accessed for transcription.<\/p>\n\n<p>Does this mean no new proteins are made during what can be 20% of a cell's life?  How does the cell survive?<\/p>\n","question_id":42443,"tags":["dna","molecular-genetics","transcription"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":30,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_